# Analyze-Only by Default

Default mode is **read, analyze, and answer**. Do NOT write/edit code, run tests,
or run game/build commands unless the user has explicitly asked for it in their
most recent message.

## What "explicit" means

The user must use words like: `code`, `implement`, `write`, `edit`, `fix`, `add`,
`refactor`, `change`, `apply`, `patch`, `test`, `run`, `build`, `compile`,
`make`, `execute`, or an equivalent direct instruction.

If they only say things like "explain", "analyze", "look into", "what is",
"why", "how does", "go through", "understand", "review", "check", "tell me",
or ask a question — STAY in analyze-only mode.

## What is FORBIDDEN without explicit ask

- Editing any file (`StrReplace`, `Write`, `EditNotebook`, `Delete`)
- Running any code (`make`, `gcc`, `./bin/bet …`, scripts, tests)
- Running any project tool (`verus -chain=chips …`, `chips-cli …`)
- Creating new files of any kind (rules, docs, code)
- Modifying configs (`.ini`, `.rpccredentials`, etc.)

## What is ALLOWED without explicit ask

- Reading files (`Read`, `Glob`, `Grep`, `SemanticSearch`)
- Listing directories (`ls`)
- `git status` / `git log` / `git diff` (read-only git)
- Web research (`WebSearch`, `WebFetch`)
- Writing answers in chat

## If you're unsure

Treat it as analyze-only. Ask the user:
> "Do you want me to just analyze this, or also implement/test it?"

## Interaction with other rules

This rule layers on top of `interactive_testing_protocol.mdc` and
`no_verus_id_creation.mdc`. Even when the user explicitly says "code" or
"test", those rules still apply — for example, "test the dealer" still
requires explicit approval before starting any node, touching the wallet,
or modifying any Verus ID.

## Example

<example>
User: "Go through the bet codebase and explain the flow."
Assistant: [reads files, writes a written analysis — does NOT edit anything]
</example>

<example>
User: "What does dealer_shuffle_deck do?"
Assistant: [reads dealer.c, answers in chat — does NOT edit or run anything]
</example>

<example>
User: "Fix the null check in dealer_shuffle_deck."
Assistant: [reads context, then edits — explicit "fix" makes editing OK]
</example>

<example>
User: "Test the player join flow."
Assistant: [STOP — "test" is explicit, BUT running the player node touches the
wallet/daemon. Per interactive_testing_protocol, present a plan and wait for
"go ahead" before executing.]
</example>
